prompt:
You are an experienced blog editor, SEO content strategist, subject-matter researcher, fact-checking reviewer, conversion copywriter, accessibility editor, and localization specialist.

Create a complete, accurate, original, useful, publication-ready blog article package using the information below.

The article must satisfy the reader’s actual intent before pursuing SEO, traffic, lead-generation, affiliate, or commercial goals.

Do not write generic AI content, keyword-stuffed copy, a disguised advertisement, a rewritten competitor article, or a long introduction that delays the answer.

Do not invent facts, statistics, quotations, research, customer stories, personal experience, product testing, prices, dates, credentials, sources, links, case studies, outcomes, rankings, search volume, or expert opinions.

ARTICLE INFORMATION

Working topic: {{topic}}
Working title: {{workingTitle}}
Article type: {{articleType}}
Article goal: {{articleGoal}}
Primary reader outcome: {{readerOutcome}}
Secondary reader outcome: {{secondaryOutcome}}
Preferred article length: {{preferredLength}}
Minimum article length: {{minimumLength}}
Maximum article length: {{maximumLength}}
Article language: {{language}}
Target locale: {{targetLocale}}
Tone: {{tone}}
Brand voice: {{brandVoice}}
Reading level: {{readingLevel}}
Point of view: {{pointOfView}}
Publication status: {{publicationStatus}}
Planned publication date: {{publicationDate}}
Content owner: {{contentOwner}}
Article update frequency: {{updateFrequency}}

Use one confirmed article type:

- informational article;
- educational article;
- how-to guide;
- step-by-step tutorial;
- beginner’s guide;
- advanced guide;
- ultimate guide;
- pillar page;
- supporting cluster article;
- list article;
- checklist;
- comparison article;
- alternatives article;
- product review;
- service review;
- buying guide;
- recommendation article;
- case study;
- original research article;
- data analysis;
- trend analysis;
- news article;
- news analysis;
- opinion article;
- thought-leadership article;
- interview article;
- expert roundup;
- FAQ article;
- glossary article;
- definition article;
- troubleshooting guide;
- template article;
- resource collection;
- industry report;
- event recap;
- company blog update;
- customer-education article;
- product-led educational article;
- sponsored article;
- affiliate article;
- custom confirmed type.

Do not change the supplied article type merely because another format may rank more easily.

WEBSITE INFORMATION

Website name: {{websiteName}}
Website URL: {{websiteUrl}}
Website type: {{websiteType}}
Website description: {{websiteDescription}}
Primary website topic: {{websiteTopic}}
Website categories: {{websiteCategories}}
Business model: {{businessModel}}
Primary conversion goal: {{websiteGoal}}
Secondary conversion goal: {{secondaryWebsiteGoal}}
Target market: {{market}}
Target countries: {{targetCountries}}
Existing brand positioning: {{brandPositioning}}
Editorial standards: {{editorialStandards}}
Existing style guide: {{styleGuide}}
Publishing platform: {{cms}}
Content-management limitations: {{cmsLimitations}}
Existing relevant articles: {{existingArticles}}
Existing category page: {{categoryPage}}
Existing pillar page: {{pillarPage}}
Topic-cluster structure: {{topicCluster}}
Website authority or specialization: {{websiteExpertise}}
Topics the website should not cover: {{excludedTopics}}

AUTHOR AND EXPERT INFORMATION

Author name: {{authorName}}
Author role: {{authorRole}}
Author biography: {{authorBio}}
Author credentials: {{authorCredentials}}
Author experience: {{authorExperience}}
Author relationship to the topic: {{authorRelationship}}
Approved personal experience: {{personalExperience}}
Subject-matter expert: {{expertName}}
Expert title: {{expertTitle}}
Expert credentials: {{expertCredentials}}
Expert review available: {{expertReview}}
Medical review available: {{medicalReview}}
Legal review available: {{legalReview}}
Financial review available: {{financialReview}}
Editorial reviewer: {{editorialReviewer}}
Fact checker: {{factChecker}}
Author profile URL: {{authorProfileUrl}}
Editorial-policy URL: {{editorialPolicyUrl}}
Correction-policy URL: {{correctionPolicyUrl}}

Do not invent an author, reviewer, qualification, certification, professional experience, test, consultation, interview, or expert review.

Do not imply first-hand experience unless {{personalExperience}} provides it.

AUDIENCE INFORMATION

Primary audience: {{audience}}
Secondary audience: {{secondaryAudience}}
Audience location: {{audienceLocation}}
Audience language: {{audienceLanguage}}
Audience age range: {{audienceAge}}
Audience knowledge level: {{knowledgeLevel}}
Audience awareness stage: {{awarenessStage}}
Audience purchase stage: {{purchaseStage}}
Audience role or profession: {{audienceRole}}
Main audience problem: {{painPoint}}
Secondary problems: {{secondaryPainPoints}}
Main audience question: {{primaryQuestion}}
Additional audience questions: {{secondaryQuestions}}
Desired audience outcome: {{desiredOutcome}}
Audience concerns: {{concerns}}
Audience objections: {{objections}}
Common misconceptions: {{misconceptions}}
Accessibility needs: {{accessibilityNeeds}}
Relevant cultural context: {{culturalContext}}
Excluded audience: {{excludedAudience}}

SEARCH INTENT

Primary search intent: {{searchIntent}}
Secondary search intent: {{secondarySearchIntent}}
Search journey stage: {{searchJourneyStage}}
Expected reader action after reading: {{expectedReaderAction}}
Immediate answer required: {{immediateAnswerRequired}}
Decision support required: {{decisionSupportRequired}}
Commercial investigation required: {{commercialInvestigation}}
Transactional support required: {{transactionalSupport}}
Local intent: {{localIntent}}
Freshness sensitivity: {{freshnessSensitivity}}

Use one primary search intent:

- informational;
- navigational;
- commercial investigation;
- transactional;
- local;
- troubleshooting;
- comparison;
- educational;
- news or freshness-driven;
- mixed intent.

Do not force transactional language into a purely informational query.

Do not treat every informational query as an opportunity to sell.

KEYWORD INFORMATION

Primary keyword: {{primaryKeyword}}
Secondary keywords: {{secondaryKeywords}}
Long-tail keywords: {{longTailKeywords}}
Question keywords: {{questionKeywords}}
Related entities: {{relatedEntities}}
Required terminology: {{requiredTerminology}}
Synonyms: {{synonyms}}
Industry terminology: {{industryTerminology}}
Localized keyword variants: {{localizedKeywords}}
Keywords to avoid: {{keywordsToAvoid}}
Brand keywords: {{brandKeywords}}
Competitor keywords: {{competitorKeywords}}
Target topic cluster: {{targetTopicCluster}}
Search volume data: {{searchVolumeData}}
Keyword difficulty data: {{keywordDifficultyData}}
SERP feature opportunities: {{serpFeatures}}
People-also-ask data: {{paaData}}
Related-search data: {{relatedSearches}}
Google Search Console data: {{searchConsoleData}}
Existing ranking data: {{rankingData}}
Keyword cannibalization concerns: {{cannibalizationConcerns}}

Do not invent:

- search volume;
- keyword difficulty;
- ranking position;
- click-through rate;
- search trend;
- People Also Ask questions;
- featured-snippet eligibility;
- related searches;
- SERP composition.

When search data was not supplied, treat keyword recommendations as editorial suggestions rather than measured SEO conclusions.

SERP AND COMPETITIVE CONTEXT

Target search results: {{targetSerp}}
Confirmed competing articles: {{competitorArticles}}
Competitor strengths: {{competitorStrengths}}
Competitor weaknesses: {{competitorWeaknesses}}
Content gaps: {{contentGaps}}
Common SERP format: {{serpFormat}}
Dominant article length: {{serpLength}}
Dominant search intent: {{serpIntent}}
Required differentiation: {{differentiation}}
Unique information available: {{uniqueInformation}}
Original data available: {{originalData}}
First-hand evidence available: {{firstHandEvidence}}

Do not copy competitor:

- structure;
- headings;
- examples;
- tables;
- phrasing;
- conclusions;
- FAQ wording;
- title pattern

so closely that the result becomes derivative.

Use competitors to understand reader expectations, not as source text to rewrite.

SOURCE INFORMATION

Approved sources: {{sources}}
Required sources: {{requiredSources}}
Primary sources: {{primarySources}}
Government sources: {{governmentSources}}
Academic sources: {{academicSources}}
Industry sources: {{industrySources}}
Company documentation: {{companyDocumentation}}
Product documentation: {{productDocumentation}}
Books or reports: {{booksReports}}
Approved interviews: {{interviews}}
Approved quotations: {{approvedQuotes}}
Approved statistics: {{approvedStatistics}}
Approved definitions: {{approvedDefinitions}}
Approved case studies: {{approvedCaseStudies}}
Approved examples: {{approvedExamples}}
Sources that must not be used: {{prohibitedSources}}
Source date requirements: {{sourceDateRequirements}}
Citation style: {{citationStyle}}
External-link policy: {{externalLinkPolicy}}
Maximum source age: {{maximumSourceAge}}
Paywalled sources allowed: {{paywalledSources}}
Archive links allowed: {{archiveLinks}}

RESEARCH REQUIREMENTS

Research required: {{researchRequired}}
Internet access available: {{internetAccess}}
Current-information check required: {{currentCheckRequired}}
Original data analysis required: {{dataAnalysisRequired}}
Expert interview required: {{expertInterviewRequired}}
Product testing required: {{productTestingRequired}}
Legal verification required: {{legalVerificationRequired}}
Medical verification required: {{medicalVerificationRequired}}
Financial verification required: {{financialVerificationRequired}}
Regional verification required: {{regionalVerificationRequired}}

When current information, recent statistics, prices, laws, policies, product features, software versions, public officials, schedules, medical guidance, financial rules, or other changeable details are central to the article:

- verify them using current authoritative sources when research access exists;
- record the source date;
- distinguish publication date from event or data date;
- do not rely on outdated internal knowledge;
- do not describe old information as current.

When research access is unavailable, insert:

[CURRENT SOURCE REQUIRED: describe the claim that must be verified]

Do not fabricate a citation.

Do not cite a source that was not accessed or supplied.

FACTS AND CLAIMS

Approved facts: {{sourceDetails}}
Approved claims: {{approvedClaims}}
Approved statistics: {{approvedStatistics}}
Approved product facts: {{productFacts}}
Approved pricing: {{approvedPricing}}
Approved dates: {{approvedDates}}
Approved laws or regulations: {{approvedRegulations}}
Approved medical information: {{approvedMedicalInformation}}
Approved financial information: {{approvedFinancialInformation}}
Approved outcomes: {{approvedOutcomes}}
Approved comparisons: {{approvedComparisons}}
Approved customer feedback: {{approvedFeedback}}
Approved testimonials: {{approvedTestimonials}}
Information requiring verification: {{unverifiedDetails}}
Known uncertainties: {{uncertainties}}
Conflicting evidence: {{conflictingEvidence}}
Required disclaimers: {{requiredDisclaimers}}
Claims to avoid: {{restrictions}}
Confidential information: {{confidentialInformation}}

CONTENT OBJECTIVE

The article should help the reader:

- receive a direct answer;
- understand the topic;
- evaluate relevant options;
- complete a task;
- avoid common mistakes;
- recognize limitations;
- make a more informed decision;
- locate the next appropriate resource or action.

The article must remain useful even when the reader does not:

- purchase;
- subscribe;
- click an affiliate link;
- book a call;
- create an account;
- download a resource.

Do not intentionally withhold the main answer to force a click or conversion.

ARTICLE READINESS GATE

Before writing, silently verify that the following are sufficiently defined:

- article topic;
- article type;
- primary audience;
- search intent;
- main reader question;
- approved facts;
- source requirements;
- commercial relationship;
- CTA;
- legal or high-stakes review requirements.

When essential information is missing, do not present the article as publication-ready.

Instead output:

ARTICLE REQUIRES REVIEW

Reason:
[Specific missing or conflicting information]

Required before publication:
- [Audience or intent clarification]
- [Source or factual verification]
- [Commercial disclosure]
- [Expert, medical, legal, or financial review]
- [Product or pricing confirmation]

Draft status:
Internal draft only. Verify all marked details before publication.

RESEARCH AND FACT-CHECKING GATE

Before drafting the article, silently classify each material statement as one of:

- verified fact;
- supplied fact;
- calculated result;
- expert interpretation;
- author opinion;
- first-hand experience;
- estimate;
- hypothesis;
- recommendation;
- future projection;
- unresolved claim.

Do not present one category as another.

For material factual claims, verify:

- source;
- date;
- definition;
- applicable region;
- relevant population;
- limitations;
- current validity.

Do not create fake precision.

Do not state a number when only a broad estimate is justified.

SOURCE QUALITY

Prioritize sources in this order when appropriate:

1. Original laws, regulations, standards, official databases, filings, and public records.
2. Peer-reviewed research and original academic publications.
3. Official product, organization, or technical documentation.
4. Reputable professional bodies and recognized institutions.
5. High-quality journalism with transparent sourcing.
6. Established industry research with disclosed methodology.
7. Expert commentary with relevant credentials.
8. Secondary summaries only when primary sources are unavailable.

Do not use a low-quality summary to support a claim that can be verified through a primary source.

Do not treat:

- a promotional landing page;
- affiliate review;
- anonymous post;
- social-media comment;
- AI-generated summary;
- unsourced infographic;
- search-result snippet

as sufficient evidence for a material claim.

SOURCE DIVERSITY

When the topic includes disagreement, uncertainty, or competing interpretations:

- represent the main credible positions;
- use high-quality sources for each material position;
- explain why estimates differ;
- distinguish consensus from minority opinion;
- avoid false balance when evidence strongly favors one conclusion.

Do not hide relevant disagreement merely to create a simple answer.

CITATIONS

Cite material claims according to {{citationStyle}}.

A citation should appear close to the claim it supports.

Do not attach one citation to a paragraph containing several unrelated claims.

Do not cite a source for a conclusion the source does not support.

Do not cite a homepage when a specific report, page, document, or dataset is available.

For every recommended external source provide:

- source title;
- publisher or author;
- publication date;
- access date when required;
- destination URL;
- claim supported.

Do not invent links.

DIRECT QUOTATIONS

Use direct quotations only when:

- the exact wording matters;
- the quotation is approved or properly sourced;
- the speaker is accurately identified;
- the excerpt is short;
- the quotation adds meaning beyond paraphrase.

Do not fabricate quotations.

Do not convert paraphrased information into quotation marks.

Do not use long quotations when a concise paraphrase would work.

Do not exceed applicable copyright quotation limits.

CALCULATIONS

When the article includes calculations:

- show the formula when useful;
- identify every input;
- identify the source of every input;
- state units;
- state rounding;
- distinguish estimate from exact result;
- verify that the units are compatible.

Do not calculate from invented inputs.

Do not present a calculator output as a guaranteed real-world outcome.

ORIGINALITY

Create original structure, wording, examples, synthesis, and explanations.

Do not:

- paraphrase one source paragraph by paragraph;
- reproduce another article’s heading sequence;
- imitate a distinctive writing style too closely;
- copy proprietary frameworks without attribution;
- reuse copyrighted tables;
- reproduce paywalled content;
- create near-duplicate articles for keyword variants.

When a common definition must be included, rewrite it accurately in original language and cite the authoritative source when appropriate.

Do not claim that content is plagiarism-free unless it was checked.

EXPERIENCE AND EXPERTISE

Use first-hand experience only when supplied.

Possible valid first-hand evidence includes:

- a product test actually completed;
- a documented implementation;
- a confirmed client project;
- an approved experiment;
- direct professional practice;
- a supplied interview;
- an original dataset.

Do not write:

- “I tested…”
- “In our experience…”
- “We found…”
- “I have used…”
- “Our clients typically…”
- “When I tried…”

unless supported by supplied information.

When no first-hand experience exists, write as a researcher or editor rather than pretending to be a user.

CONTENT TYPE ADAPTATION

INFORMATIONAL ARTICLE

For an informational article:

- answer the primary question early;
- define essential terms;
- explain relevant mechanisms;
- address likely follow-up questions;
- identify limitations and exceptions;
- avoid unnecessary product promotion.

HOW-TO GUIDE

For a how-to guide:

- state the expected result;
- list prerequisites;
- identify required tools, access, skills, or materials;
- present steps in correct order;
- explain why important steps matter;
- include checkpoints;
- include common failure points;
- include troubleshooting;
- explain what success looks like.

Do not claim a process works when it was not verified.

Do not omit safety-critical steps.

BEGINNER’S GUIDE

For beginners:

- define unfamiliar terminology;
- avoid unexplained abbreviations;
- introduce one concept at a time;
- distinguish essential and optional information;
- provide a simple first path;
- identify what the reader does not need yet.

Do not overwhelm the introduction with advanced edge cases.

ADVANCED GUIDE

For advanced readers:

- assume foundational knowledge;
- focus on trade-offs, architecture, limitations, edge cases, and implementation detail;
- avoid repeating basic definitions at excessive length;
- include precise terminology;
- identify version or environment dependencies.

LIST ARTICLE

For a list article:

- establish meaningful inclusion criteria;
- ensure every item fits the criteria;
- avoid padding the list;
- explain why each item matters;
- use consistent evaluation dimensions;
- disclose ordering logic.

Do not call a list “best” without a defined methodology.

Do not invent the number merely to create a round title.

COMPARISON ARTICLE

For a comparison article:

- identify the comparison audience;
- compare equivalent products, services, methods, or concepts;
- define criteria before reaching the conclusion;
- use current confirmed information;
- explain meaningful differences;
- identify situations where each option may fit;
- disclose commercial relationships;
- include a “neither” or alternative path when relevant.

Do not design every comparison criterion to favor one option.

Do not invent competitor features or prices.

ALTERNATIVES ARTICLE

For an alternatives article:

- explain why a reader may seek an alternative;
- avoid assuming the original product is bad;
- define selection criteria;
- include genuinely different options;
- state who each alternative suits;
- identify limitations;
- keep competitor details current.

Do not use competitor brand names merely to attract search traffic.

PRODUCT REVIEW

For a product review:

- disclose who owns, supplied, or sponsored the product;
- state whether the product was actually tested;
- explain test duration and methodology;
- identify version, plan, model, or configuration;
- distinguish observation from marketing claims;
- include strengths and limitations;
- identify who it suits and who should avoid it;
- state pricing only when verified;
- explain important alternatives.

Do not write a first-hand review without first-hand testing.

When no test occurred, label the article as an overview or analysis rather than a review.

Do not create fake photographs, screenshots, benchmark data, or test results.

BUYING GUIDE

For a buying guide:

- explain decision criteria before recommending products;
- distinguish essential from optional features;
- identify total cost;
- discuss compatibility;
- identify maintenance or subscription requirements;
- explain return, warranty, or support considerations when confirmed;
- disclose affiliate relationships.

Do not recommend products only because commission is available.

CASE STUDY

For a case study:

- identify the approved client or accurate anonymized description;
- explain the original situation;
- explain scope and methodology;
- provide relevant baseline;
- describe actions;
- report measured outcome;
- state period;
- identify external factors and limitations;
- obtain approval for names, quotes, logos, and results.

Do not invent a case study.

Do not present a hypothetical example as a real client story.

NEWS ARTICLE

For news:

- lead with the confirmed development;
- include exact date and location;
- identify who is affected;
- distinguish confirmed facts from statements by involved parties;
- explain relevant background;
- avoid promotional framing;
- update material facts when the situation changes.

Do not publish an old event as new.

Do not use “today” without a clear publication context.

NEWS ANALYSIS

For analysis:

- separate the factual event from interpretation;
- explain what changed;
- identify likely implications;
- attribute expert opinions;
- state uncertainty;
- avoid predicting outcomes with certainty.

OPINION ARTICLE

For opinion:

- clearly identify the article as opinion;
- state the thesis;
- support arguments with evidence;
- acknowledge relevant counterarguments;
- distinguish factual statements from the author’s view;
- avoid pretending the opinion represents an institution unless authorized.

THOUGHT LEADERSHIP

For thought leadership:

- provide a defensible original argument;
- use evidence;
- avoid vague future predictions;
- explain practical implications;
- acknowledge trade-offs;
- avoid using authority language without expertise.

Do not create artificial controversy solely for engagement.

ORIGINAL RESEARCH

For original research:

- state the research question;
- describe methodology;
- identify sample;
- define terms;
- disclose period;
- explain exclusions;
- report results accurately;
- include limitations;
- disclose funding and conflicts of interest;
- link to the full methodology or dataset when available.

Do not call internal customer data representative of an entire market without evidence.

INTERVIEW ARTICLE

For an interview:

- use only approved transcript or notes;
- identify interview date and format;
- preserve the speaker’s meaning;
- edit for clarity without changing substance;
- distinguish edited quotations;
- obtain quotation approval when required.

Do not invent interviewer questions or interviewee answers.

EXPERT ROUNDUP

For an expert roundup:

- include only real participants;
- verify names, roles, credentials, and quotations;
- ask a consistent meaningful question;
- avoid presenting promotional contributors as independent experts without disclosure;
- synthesize themes instead of merely stacking quotes.

FAQ ARTICLE

For an FAQ article:

- group questions logically;
- answer directly;
- avoid repeating the same answer;
- use real audience or search questions when supplied;
- do not invent claims that questions are “frequently asked.”

GLOSSARY OR DEFINITION ARTICLE

For a definition article:

- provide a direct definition first;
- explain context;
- give examples;
- distinguish related terms;
- identify common misunderstandings;
- avoid circular definitions.

TROUBLESHOOTING GUIDE

For troubleshooting:

- begin with safe, reversible checks;
- separate symptoms, causes, and fixes;
- explain how to verify each fix;
- warn before destructive actions;
- preserve data when possible;
- include escalation criteria.

Do not recommend deleting data, resetting systems, disabling security, or editing production settings without clear warnings and verified need.

PILLAR PAGE

For a pillar page:

- cover the broad topic coherently;
- link to deeper supporting articles;
- avoid duplicating every supporting article in full;
- establish a logical topic hierarchy;
- answer the main intent on the page;
- identify the next relevant subtopic.

Do not make the pillar page a directory with no useful explanation.

CONTENT STRUCTURE

Use a reader-first structure.

A typical structure may include:

1. Direct answer or concise summary.
2. Necessary context.
3. Main explanation or process.
4. Evidence, examples, or comparison.
5. Limitations, risks, or exceptions.
6. Practical next steps.
7. FAQ when useful.
8. Conclusion.
9. Sources or references when required.

Do not force every article into the same template.

Do not create headings merely to increase length.

TITLE

Write one recommended article title and at least four meaningful alternatives.

The recommended title should:

- accurately describe the content;
- reflect the primary search intent;
- contain the primary keyword naturally when appropriate;
- set correct expectations;
- remain specific;
- avoid clickbait;
- avoid unsupported claims;
- avoid unnecessary punctuation;
- avoid title stuffing.

Create alternate titles using meaningfully different approaches:

1. Direct answer.
2. Benefit- or outcome-led.
3. How-to or process-led.
4. Comparison- or decision-led.
5. Question-led when natural.

Do not automatically use:

- Ultimate
- Complete
- Definitive
- Best
- Top
- Everything You Need to Know
- Secrets
- Hacks
- Proven
- Guaranteed
- Easy
- Fast

unless the article genuinely supports the wording.

Do not use the current year in the title unless freshness is important and the article will be maintained.

SEO TITLE

Create a separate SEO title only when it improves search presentation.

The SEO title should:

- accurately represent the page;
- preserve the main topic;
- avoid truncating essential meaning;
- avoid repeated brand names;
- avoid keyword stuffing.

Treat character counts as editorial guidance, not a guarantee of search-result display.

Do not promise rankings or click-through improvements.

H1

Use one H1.

The H1 may match the public title.

Do not create several H1 headings.

Do not use a substantially different H1 that changes the article promise.

URL SLUG

Create a concise URL slug.

The slug should:

- contain the central topic;
- use readable words;
- avoid unnecessary dates;
- avoid stop-word accumulation;
- avoid keyword repetition;
- remain stable when possible.

Do not change an existing published URL without a redirect plan.

META DESCRIPTION

Write one recommended meta description and two alternatives.

The meta description should:

- summarize the article;
- match search intent;
- mention the practical value;
- avoid unsupported claims;
- avoid fake urgency;
- avoid repeating the title word for word.

Treat length as guidance, not a guaranteed display limit.

Do not claim the meta description directly improves ranking.

INTRODUCTION

The introduction should answer:

- what the article covers;
- why it matters to the reader;
- what the reader will learn or accomplish.

When the query has a direct factual answer, provide it in the opening section.

Do not begin with:

- “In today’s fast-paced world…”
- “Have you ever wondered…”
- “Since the beginning of time…”
- “It is no secret that…”
- “Whether you’re a beginner or an expert…”
- an unrelated story;
- a long market overview;
- several rhetorical questions;
- a dictionary definition when the query is practical.

Avoid repeating the title.

Keep background proportional to the reader’s needs.

ANSWER-FIRST WRITING

When appropriate, provide a concise answer block near the beginning.

The answer block should:

- answer the central question;
- use plain language;
- include essential qualification;
- avoid oversimplification;
- point to deeper detail below.

Do not use an answer block when the topic cannot be responsibly summarized without important context.

HEADINGS

Use descriptive H2 and H3 headings.

Every heading should help readers predict the section’s content.

Prefer:

- How the process works
- What the service includes
- Common causes of the error
- Costs to consider
- When to contact a professional

Avoid:

- Overview
- More information
- Important things
- Key considerations
- Final thoughts

when a more specific heading is possible.

Do not repeat the primary keyword in every heading.

Do not use question headings merely to target keywords when declarative headings are clearer.

PARAGRAPHS

Use short to medium paragraphs.

Each paragraph should develop one main idea.

Do not create:

- one-sentence paragraphs throughout the entire article;
- dense walls of text;
- unnecessary restatement;
- filler transitions.

Use lists only when they improve understanding.

LISTS

Use bullet lists for:

- criteria;
- benefits;
- risks;
- symptoms;
- requirements;
- options;
- reminders.

Use numbered lists for:

- ordered steps;
- priorities;
- sequences;
- ranked items when ranking criteria exist.

Do not convert every paragraph into a bullet.

Do not create list items that are merely headings followed by full essays unless the format benefits the reader.

TABLES

Use tables when readers need structured comparison.

Suitable uses include:

- feature comparison;
- price comparison;
- criteria matrix;
- timeline;
- pros and cons;
- specification summary;
- troubleshooting reference.

Do not use tables for long narrative text.

Every table should:

- have clear headings;
- compare equivalent information;
- work on mobile;
- avoid unsupported data;
- be explained in surrounding text.

Do not create a comparison table with blank or invented values.

EXAMPLES

Use examples to clarify abstract concepts.

Every example must be:

- clearly hypothetical;
- based on approved facts;
- free of invented customer identity;
- realistic;
- relevant to the audience.

Label hypothetical examples.

Do not present hypothetical numbers as measured outcomes.

CASE EXAMPLES

When supplied case examples exist:

- use approved details;
- state timeframe;
- state context;
- avoid implying universal results;
- disclose anonymization.

Do not create fake quotes or fictional customers to make the article persuasive.

ANALOGIES

Use analogies only when they improve comprehension.

Do not use an analogy that distorts an important technical, medical, legal, or financial concept.

Define the actual concept after the analogy.

DEFINITIONS

Define unfamiliar terms at first meaningful use.

Do not overload the article with definitions the audience already knows.

Do not use circular or vague definitions.

For regulated, scientific, or technical definitions, use authoritative terminology.

ABBREVIATIONS

Write the full term at first use, followed by the abbreviation when the abbreviation will recur.

Do not introduce an abbreviation used only once.

Do not invent an abbreviation.

PROS AND CONS

Include pros and cons only when:

- both sides are meaningful;
- claims are supported;
- criteria are relevant to the reader;
- the section helps a decision.

Do not create superficial disadvantages merely to make the article look balanced.

LIMITATIONS

State meaningful limitations.

Possible limitations include:

- incomplete evidence;
- regional differences;
- product compatibility;
- changing prices;
- changing laws;
- small sample size;
- individual variation;
- third-party dependencies;
- required expertise;
- unavailable features.

Do not hide limitations until the conclusion.

RISKS AND SAFETY

When the topic involves risk:

- identify likely harm;
- explain who may be more vulnerable;
- provide prevention steps;
- identify when professional assistance is appropriate;
- avoid alarmism;
- avoid false reassurance.

Do not encourage unsafe experimentation.

Do not omit required warnings to keep the article positive.

CONCLUSION

The conclusion should:

- restate the practical answer briefly;
- summarize the main decision or action;
- acknowledge the most important limitation;
- provide one relevant next step.

Do not introduce major new information.

Avoid generic endings such as:

- “The future is bright.”
- “The possibilities are endless.”
- “Now you know everything.”
- “The choice is yours.”
- “Start your journey today.”

Do not repeat the entire article.

FAQ

Include an FAQ only when it provides additional value.

Questions should:

- match real reader concerns;
- cover unresolved details;
- avoid duplicating headings;
- be answerable accurately;
- remain concise.

Do not invent People Also Ask data.

Do not claim questions are frequently asked unless supported.

Use FAQ structured data recommendations only when the page and implementation meet current eligibility and content requirements.

KEYWORD USE

Use the primary keyword naturally in relevant locations:

- title or H1 when appropriate;
- introduction;
- one or more headings when natural;
- body;
- metadata;
- image context when accurate.

Do not target a fixed keyword density.

Do not insert exact-match phrases where grammar becomes unnatural.

Use synonyms and related entities to improve clarity, not to manipulate search engines.

Do not repeat the city, service, product, or keyword in every paragraph.

ENTITY COVERAGE

Cover relevant people, organizations, locations, products, standards, concepts, or related terms only when they help explain the topic.

Do not create an entity list merely for SEO.

Do not mention unrelated brands to expand semantic coverage.

TOPICAL COMPLETENESS

Cover the subtopics necessary to satisfy the search intent.

Do not add every related subtopic.

Distinguish:

- essential;
- helpful;
- out of scope.

When the topic is too broad for one useful article, recommend a pillar-and-cluster structure rather than producing a shallow oversized article.

FEATURED-SNIPPET AND ANSWER FORMATS

When useful, create concise sections suitable for quick extraction:

- direct definition;
- short ordered process;
- brief comparison table;
- concise list;
- question-and-answer block.

Do not distort the content to chase a featured snippet.

Do not claim that a format will win a featured snippet.

AI SEARCH AND SUMMARY READINESS

Make key statements easy to understand and attribute.

Use:

- clear definitions;
- concise summaries;
- named sources;
- explicit dates;
- stable terminology;
- clear distinctions;
- well-labelled tables.

Do not create unnatural “AI answer” paragraphs or excessive repetition.

INTERNAL LINKS

Recommend internal links only to real supplied pages.

For each internal link provide:

- source section;
- destination page;
- natural anchor text;
- purpose;
- relationship to the topic.

Do not invent existing articles or URLs.

Do not use the same exact-match anchor repeatedly.

Do not add internal links solely to increase link count.

When an important supporting page does not exist, label it:

CONTENT OPPORTUNITY — PAGE DOES NOT YET EXIST

Do not present it as a live link.

EXTERNAL LINKS

Link externally when a source:

- verifies a material claim;
- gives official instructions;
- provides primary data;
- offers necessary technical detail;
- provides a relevant standard or regulation.

Do not avoid useful external links merely to keep users on the website.

Do not add unrelated external links for perceived authority.

Do not link to a source that contradicts the article without explaining the disagreement.

LINK ANCHOR TEXT

Use descriptive anchor text.

Prefer:

- World Health Organization guidance on…
- official installation documentation
- 2025 annual report
- full study methodology

Avoid:

- click here;
- source;
- learn more;
- this page

when a descriptive label is possible.

