- avoid phrases such as “today only” unless a real personalized deadline system exists and is disclosed.

LIVE WORKSHOP

For a workshop:

- define the task attendees will complete;
- list prerequisites;
- explain what materials or software are required;
- include work periods and pauses;
- provide checkpoints;
- state what attendees should have by the end;
- avoid promising completion when the task depends on individual circumstances.

PRODUCT DEMONSTRATION

For a demonstration:

- show real available functionality;
- organize the demo around user tasks;
- explain setup requirements;
- identify limitations;
- avoid demonstrating mock features as live functionality;
- include fallback screenshots or a recorded backup when available;
- reserve time for product questions.

PANEL DISCUSSION

For a panel:

- establish one central question;
- introduce each panelist concisely;
- give each participant a distinct role or perspective;
- create balanced moderator questions;
- prevent repetitive answers;
- reserve time for audience questions;
- do not script panelist answers unless approved responses were supplied.

INTERVIEW

For an interview:

- create the host introduction;
- explain why the guest is relevant;
- organize questions into a logical progression;
- include optional follow-ups;
- do not invent guest answers;
- leave realistic time for responses.

When no guest answers were supplied, use:

HOST:
[Question]

FOLLOW-UP OPTIONS:
- [Follow-up]
- [Follow-up]

GUEST:
[Response not scripted]

SALES WEBINAR

For a sales webinar:

- provide genuine educational value;
- establish the problem and decision context;
- explain the method or framework;
- transition clearly into the offer;
- disclose that the webinar includes a commercial offer;
- explain pricing, eligibility, limitations, and terms accurately;
- avoid withholding the entire solution solely to force a purchase;
- avoid exaggerated transformation stories.

CUSTOMER ONBOARDING WEBINAR

For onboarding:

- help users complete the first meaningful task;
- explain account and access requirements;
- demonstrate the core workflow;
- prevent common setup mistakes;
- direct users to approved support resources;
- avoid turning onboarding into an unrelated upsell presentation.

DURATION AND PACING

Create a realistic agenda matching {{duration}} minutes.

Account for:

- opening and housekeeping;
- presenter introduction;
- core teaching;
- examples;
- demonstrations;
- audience interaction;
- pauses;
- transitions;
- offer presentation;
- Q&A;
- closing.

Do not divide all sections evenly.

Prioritize the sections that deliver the main promise.

Suggested pacing guidance:

For a 30-minute webinar:

- 2–4 minutes: opening and expectations;
- 18–22 minutes: core content;
- 3–5 minutes: recap or CTA;
- 3–5 minutes: questions.

For a 45–60-minute webinar:

- 3–5 minutes: opening;
- 30–40 minutes: teaching or demonstration;
- 5–10 minutes: offer or next step;
- 8–15 minutes: Q&A.

Use these only as guidance.

Adjust timing to the actual format.

Do not create a 15-minute sales pitch inside a short educational session unless explicitly requested.

TITLE

Write one recommended webinar title and four alternate titles.

All titles should:

- accurately represent the session;
- communicate the primary topic or outcome;
- identify the intended audience when useful;
- remain clear outside the registration page;
- avoid unsupported claims;
- avoid excessive length;
- avoid generic event language.

Use different approaches:

1. Direct and descriptive.
2. Outcome-led.
3. Problem-led.
4. Audience-led.
5. Method- or framework-led.

Avoid titles such as:

- “The Ultimate Masterclass”
- “Change Your Life in One Hour”
- “The Secret to Guaranteed Success”
- “The Webinar You Can’t Miss”
- “The Number One Strategy”
- “Everything You Need to Know”
- “Unlock Unlimited Growth”
- “The Future of Everything”

unless the wording is factually justified.

SUBTITLE

Write one webinar subtitle.

The subtitle should:

- clarify what attendees will learn;
- explain the practical relevance;
- add information not already in the title;
- avoid repeating the complete title;
- avoid guaranteed outcomes.

REGISTRATION PAGE

Write a complete webinar registration page.

Use this structure:

1. Webinar title
2. Subtitle
3. Date, time, and time zone
4. Webinar format
5. Main attendee promise
6. Short description
7. Who it is for
8. What attendees will learn
9. What attendees will not receive or important limitations
10. Presenter information
11. Event logistics
12. Registration CTA
13. Privacy or marketing-consent note when supplied
14. FAQ
15. Commercial disclosure when relevant

REGISTRATION PAGE RULES

The page should:

- state whether the webinar is live, recorded, or evergreen;
- explain whether a replay will be available;
- identify required software, account, or experience;
- state the cost accurately;
- mention commercial content when relevant;
- explain what happens after registration;
- use one primary registration CTA;
- remain useful on mobile.

Do not:

- invent seat limits;
- add fake countdown language;
- create unsupported bonuses;
- imply certification when none exists;
- hide the presence of a sales offer;
- claim that registration closes unless a real deadline exists;
- claim that replay access is guaranteed unless confirmed.

LEARNING OUTCOMES

Write 3–5 specific learning outcomes.

Each outcome should describe what the attendee will:

- understand;
- identify;
- compare;
- evaluate;
- configure;
- create;
- practise;
- decide;
- apply.

Avoid vague outcomes such as:

- learn valuable insights;
- discover powerful secrets;
- transform your strategy;
- master everything;
- achieve success.

Do not promise that every attendee will complete or implement the outcome when that depends on individual ability or external factors.

AUDIENCE QUALIFICATION

Write a “Who this webinar is for” section.

Use specific audience situations, roles, or needs.

Also write a brief “This may not be for you if” section when relevant.

Do not use exclusion to manufacture prestige.

Use it to clarify:

- required knowledge;
- product compatibility;
- professional scope;
- geographic availability;
- budget or account requirements;
- technical prerequisites;
- topic relevance.

PRESENTER BIO

Write one concise presenter biography.

Use only approved information.

Include:

- presenter name;
- current role;
- relevant experience;
- relationship to the topic;
- one or two approved credentials when important.

Do not include unrelated career history.

Do not invent awards, media appearances, clients, qualifications, certifications, or years of experience.

AGENDA

Create a timed webinar agenda.

For every section include:

- approximate start time;
- approximate duration;
- section title;
- section goal;
- presenter action;
- audience action;
- visual or demo requirement;
- transition.

Label timing as:

Draft webinar timing — adjust during rehearsal

The agenda must fit within {{duration}} minutes.

Include buffer time for:

- technical delays;
- transitions;
- audience questions;
- demonstrations taking longer than expected.

Do not schedule every minute without flexibility.

WEBINAR SCRIPT

Write the complete presenter script where appropriate.

Separate spoken content from production instructions.

Use these labels:

PRESENTER:
[Exact spoken text]

MODERATOR:
[Exact spoken text]

PANELIST:
[Approved response or “Response not scripted”]

PRODUCTION NOTE:
[Internal instruction]

SLIDE:
[Slide title or visual]

DEMO:
[Confirmed demonstration step]

POLL:
[Approved poll]

CHAT PROMPT:
[Specific audience prompt]

PAUSE:
[Approximate pause]

Do not include internal instructions inside presenter dialogue.

OPENING SCRIPT

The opening should include:

1. A concise topic-led opening.
2. A clear explanation of what the session covers.
3. The main attendee benefit.
4. Relevant housekeeping.
5. Presenter identification.
6. A brief agenda.
7. Commercial disclosure when relevant.

Do not begin with a long biography.

Do not spend several minutes asking where attendees are joining from unless community interaction is central to the format.

Avoid:

- “We’re so excited to have you here.”
- “This webinar will change everything.”
- “You’re in exactly the right place.”
- “Stay until the end for a surprise.”
- “You won’t want to miss what’s coming.”

unless the wording naturally fits and is accurate.

HOUSEKEEPING

Include only relevant housekeeping information:

- session duration;
- whether the session is recorded;
- replay information;
- how to submit questions;
- whether chat is monitored;
- accessibility information;
- technical support;
- whether slides or resources will be shared;
- commercial disclosure.

Do not announce features unavailable on the selected platform.

CORE CONTENT

Organize the teaching into 3–5 main sections unless the topic requires another structure.

Every section should:

- contribute directly to the main promise;
- introduce one clear concept, step, or decision;
- include a useful explanation;
- include an example, exercise, visual, or demonstration when appropriate;
- mention limitations or exceptions;
- transition logically.

Do not:

- repeat the same point in several sections;
- introduce unrelated background;
- overload slides with paragraphs;
- use several unsupported statistics;
- turn every point into a product pitch;
- create artificial suspense.

FRAMEWORKS

When introducing a framework:

- give it a descriptive name;
- explain every component;
- clarify whether the framework is original, adapted, or widely used;
- do not claim ownership of a known framework;
- avoid forced acronyms;
- provide a practical example;
- explain where the framework may not apply.

Do not invent proprietary methods solely to make the webinar sound distinctive.

EXAMPLES AND CASE STUDIES

Use only supplied examples and case studies.

For every case study distinguish:

- starting situation;
- action taken;
- relevant context;
- verified result;
- limitations;
- whether the outcome is typical.

Do not imply universal results.

Do not invent customer names, revenue, conversion rates, timelines, screenshots, or quotations.

When an example is hypothetical, label it clearly:

HYPOTHETICAL EXAMPLE:
[Example]

Do not make a hypothetical example sound like a real customer success story.

PRODUCT DEMONSTRATION

When a demonstration is included, create a step-by-step demo plan.

For each step provide:

- user goal;
- screen or feature shown;
- presenter explanation;
- action performed;
- expected result;
- limitation or warning;
- fallback visual.

Do not invent product screens, buttons, menu labels, workflows, integrations, or outcomes.

Insert:

PRODUCTION NOTE:
Prepare a recorded backup or screenshots for any live demonstration.

Only include this note when backup assets can realistically be prepared.

SLIDE DECK OUTLINE

Create a complete slide-by-slide outline.

For every slide provide:

- slide number;
- slide title;
- slide purpose;
- key message;
- recommended visual;
- maximum on-slide text;
- presenter notes;
- approximate speaking time.

Recommended slide roles may include:

1. Title
2. Attendee promise
3. Agenda
4. Problem or context
5. Key concept
6. Framework
7. Example
8. Demonstration
9. Common mistake
10. Practical action
11. Recap
12. Offer or next step
13. Q&A
14. Closing

Do not force all slides.

SLIDE RULES

Slides should support the presenter rather than duplicate the full script.

Use:

- one main idea per slide;
- short headings;
- concise labels;
- simple diagrams;
- real screenshots;
- readable charts;
- relevant examples.

Avoid:

- paragraphs;
- tiny text;
- decorative stock images;
- unsupported graphs;
- fake customer comments;
- unnecessary animations;
- several competing visuals;
- placing the full presenter script on slides.

For charts:

- use only supplied data;
- label axes and units;
- state the source;
- avoid misleading scales;
- do not invent trends or projections.

AUDIENCE INTERACTION

Create interaction moments only when the platform supports them.

Possible interactions include:

- chat question;
- poll;
- short reflection;
- worksheet task;
- demonstration choice;
- Q&A;
- breakout exercise.

Every interaction should:

- support a learning objective;
- have a clear instruction;
- fit the available time;
- avoid unnecessary personal data;
- have a fallback when participation is low.

Do not add interaction merely to claim the webinar is interactive.

POLL QUESTIONS

Use approved polls when supplied.

When poll creation is requested but exact options were not supplied, create draft poll ideas labelled:

Draft poll — presenter approval required

Poll rules:

- ask one clear question;
- keep options distinct;
- avoid biased wording;
- avoid collecting sensitive information;
- do not claim the result is representative of a wider population;
- do not invent live results.

CHAT PROMPTS

Write specific chat prompts.

Avoid generic prompts such as:

- “Drop a yes in the chat.”
- “Type 1 if you agree.”
- “Who is excited?”
- “Where is everyone joining from?”

unless they serve a clear purpose.

Prefer prompts such as:

“What is the main obstacle you encounter during [specific process]?”

Do not use chat activity as fake social proof.

Q&A PREPARATION

Create a Q&A preparation section with:

- likely audience questions;
- approved answer framework;
- facts or policies to verify;
- questions that require follow-up;
- questions outside the webinar’s scope;
- sensitive questions requiring careful handling.

Do not invent definitive answers when information is unavailable.

Use:

“Based on the information confirmed for this session…”

“I don’t have enough verified information to answer that accurately.”

“That depends on [specific factor].”

“We should follow up after the session rather than speculate.”

Do not pressure the presenter to improvise legal, medical, financial, technical, or policy claims.

MODERATOR GUIDE

When a moderator is involved, create a guide containing:

- opening responsibilities;
- presenter introduction;
- chat moderation;
- technical support process;
- question selection criteria;
- time warnings;
- transition into Q&A;
- handling inappropriate comments;
- closing responsibilities.

Do not ask the moderator to fabricate enthusiasm, testimonials, attendance figures, or audience reactions.

OFFER TRANSITION

When the webinar includes an offer, create a transparent transition.

The transition should:

- connect the educational content to the next step;
- make it clear that the session is moving into a commercial section;
- explain who the offer is for;
- avoid implying that the free content was intentionally incomplete;
- avoid emotional pressure.

Example structure:

PRESENTER:
“We’ve covered the process you can apply independently. For those who want [specific additional support], I’ll briefly explain the available option.”

Do not use:

- “You have two choices…”
- “Stay stuck or invest in yourself.”
- “Serious people will act now.”
- “The price of doing nothing is…”
- “If you really want results…”

OFFER PRESENTATION

Present the offer accurately.

Include only confirmed:

- product or service name;
- intended user;
- included features;
- delivery method;
- pricing;
- payment options;
- trial;
- bonuses;
- deadline;
- eligibility;
- limitations;
- cancellation or refund terms;
- CTA link.

Explain:

- what the buyer receives;
- what is not included;
- whether implementation support exists;
- whether results depend on user action;
- whether access is recurring or one-time;
- what happens after the purchase or booking.

Do not invent value calculations, discounts, bonus prices, scarcity, or guarantees.

Do not create a fake “total value” by assigning unsupported prices to components.

URGENCY AND SCARCITY

Use urgency only when supported by a real event.

Permitted urgency may include:

- confirmed registration deadline;
- real cohort start date;
- actual capacity;
- genuine promo expiration;
- time-limited replay;
- confirmed application window.

Do not invent:

- expiring timers;
- limited seats;
- disappearing bonuses;
- price increases;
- closing enrolment;
- one-time-only offers;
- webinar-only pricing.

When no real deadline exists, do not create one.

CALL TO ACTION

Use one primary CTA.

Possible CTAs include:

- register;
- attend live;
- watch the replay;
- download an approved resource;
- book a consultation;
- start a trial;
- view plans;
- purchase a confirmed offer;
- answer a feedback survey;
- complete an onboarding task.

CTA rules:

- describe the next step clearly;
- use one destination;
- explain what happens after clicking;
- avoid several competing actions;
- do not imply something is free unless confirmed;
- do not request unnecessary personal information.

CLOSING SCRIPT

The closing should:

1. Recap the central takeaway.
2. Clarify the next practical step.
3. Mention the approved CTA.
4. Explain replay or resource access when confirmed.
5. Thank attendees briefly.
6. End the session clearly.

Do not repeat the entire webinar.

Do not introduce a new major topic.

Do not create an unconfirmed future event.

REGISTRATION CONFIRMATION EMAIL

Write one registration confirmation email.

Include:

- confirmation of registration;
- webinar title;
- date;
- time;
- time zone;
- join instructions;
- calendar reminder language;
- technical requirements;
- what to prepare;
- replay information only when confirmed;
- support contact only when supplied.

Do not invent a calendar link or join link.

REMINDER EMAIL SEQUENCE

Create an appropriate reminder sequence based on the event date.

Possible timing:

- immediately after registration;
- 24 hours before;
- 1 hour before;
- 10–15 minutes before.

Use only the number of reminders requested or appropriate.

Each reminder should have:

- timing;
- subject;
- preview text;
- concise body;
- one CTA;
- relevant preparation note.

Do not use fake urgency.

Do not claim that the session is nearly full unless confirmed.

Do not send a “starting now” reminder for an evergreen session.

NO-SHOW EMAIL

Write a no-show email only when attendance tracking exists.

The email may:

- acknowledge that the registrant could not attend;
- provide replay access when confirmed;
- summarize the session value;
- give one next step.

Do not guilt the recipient.

Do not say:

- “We missed you.”
- “You forgot.”
- “You failed to attend.”

unless the brand voice specifically supports that wording and the statement is appropriate.

ATTENDEE FOLLOW-UP EMAIL

Write one follow-up email for attendees.

Include:

- concise thank-you;
- central takeaway;
- replay or slides when confirmed;
- approved resource;
- one CTA;
- feedback request only when useful.

Do not include several competing links.

REPLAY EMAIL

Write a replay email only when a replay exists.

Include:

- replay availability;
- confirmed expiration;
- what the viewer will learn;
- timestamps or key sections when available;
- one CTA.

Do not claim that the replay expires when it does not.

POST-WEBINAR SALES EMAILS

When a sales follow-up sequence is requested:

- segment attendees and no-shows when possible;
- build on the content delivered;
- address one objection at a time;
- use only confirmed offer details;
- respect the offer deadline;
- stop sending conversion emails after purchase when the system supports it.

Do not create artificial urgency or repeat the same pitch in every email.

SOCIAL PROMOTION

Create promotional social assets only when requested.

Possible assets include:

- launch announcement;
- educational teaser;
- presenter quote;
- last-day registration reminder;
- starting-soon reminder;
- replay announcement;
- post-event takeaway.

Each social post should:

- accurately describe the webinar;
- state the date and time when relevant;
- mention the time zone;
- identify who it is for;
- use one CTA;
- avoid fake engagement;
- avoid unsupported attendee counts.

Do not write “limited seats” unless confirmed.

