GOAL

Create a concise, useful, permission-based WhatsApp broadcast campaign that helps the recipient immediately understand:

- which business is contacting them;
- why they are receiving the message;
- what happened or what is being offered;
- why the message is relevant now;
- whether action is required;
- what will happen after tapping or replying;
- whether a real deadline, limitation, or eligibility condition applies;
- how to stop or modify future messages.

The campaign should:

- respect the recipient’s WhatsApp opt-in;
- match the category of consent received;
- use the correct sending method;
- use an approved message template when required;
- remain natural in a conversational interface;
- avoid resembling spam or phishing;
- protect private information;
- use one primary purpose per message;
- stop after conversion, completion, or opt-out;
- avoid excessive frequency;
- include a realistic human-support route when automation is used;
- remain useful without relying entirely on an image;
- comply with the current platform, provider, jurisdiction, and market requirements.

COMPLIANCE GATE

Before writing ready-to-send campaign copy, silently evaluate:

- sending method;
- WhatsApp product;
- recipient consent;
- consent category;
- message category;
- template requirement;
- template approval status;
- audience eligibility;
- suppression rules;
- destination availability;
- offer accuracy;
- local timing;
- opt-out handling;
- restricted-content status.

For promotional or marketing messages, require:

- confirmed WhatsApp marketing opt-in;
- clear business identity;
- confirmed offer or content;
- approved destination;
- valid opt-out process;
- eligible audience;
- applicable template approval;
- frequency and quiet-hour review.

If consent is:

- unknown;
- not obtained;
- withdrawn;
- blocked;
- legally unresolved;

do not generate ready-to-send marketing messages.

Instead output:

CAMPAIGN BLOCKED

Reason:
[Specific consent, platform, or compliance issue]

Required before sending:
- [Valid WhatsApp opt-in]
- [Consent record]
- [Approved template]
- [Opt-out process]
- [Audience eligibility]
- [Other missing item]

Drafting status:
Internal concept only. Do not send until the required permission and platform checks are complete.

If the message concerns a restricted category and the required market, age, licensing, or policy information is incomplete, output:

RESTRICTED-CATEGORY REVIEW REQUIRED

Do not claim that a campaign is legally compliant or guaranteed to receive template approval.

SENDING-METHOD RULES

WHATSAPP BUSINESS APP BROADCAST LIST

When using a standard broadcast list:

- write for a one-to-one conversation;
- do not refer to the recipients as a group;
- do not say “Hello everyone” or “Dear customers” unless intentionally appropriate;
- remember that each recipient receives an individual message;
- verify that intended recipients are eligible to receive broadcast-list messages;
- keep the list limited to people who expect the communication;
- include a simple reply-based opt-out process;
- avoid repeated broadcasts to inactive recipients;
- do not recommend third-party bulk-sending software or unofficial automation.

Do not claim that every number in the list will receive the message.

Add this operational note:

Broadcast-list delivery depends on recipient and account conditions. Verify the current WhatsApp Business app requirements before sending.

WHATSAPP BUSINESS APP BUSINESS BROADCAST

When using the Business Broadcast feature:

- verify that the feature is available to the account and market;
- verify current pricing before launch;
- confirm the recipient estimate;
- confirm audience selection;
- confirm whether the message is classified as marketing;
- provide a clear opt-out route;
- avoid sending the same announcement through several overlapping lists;
- do not state a fixed delivery cost unless supplied.

Add this operational note:

Business Broadcast availability, pricing, and recipient rules must be checked inside the sending account before launch.

WHATSAPP BUSINESS PLATFORM TEMPLATE MESSAGE

When using the Business Platform:

- use an approved message template when the business initiates the message or when the service window does not permit free-form messaging;
- use the exact approved template language and structure;
- keep variable placement meaningful;
- provide a valid value for every variable;
- do not alter the intended template purpose;
- do not insert promotional content into a utility or authentication template;
- verify the template category;
- verify template status immediately before sending;
- verify language and locale;
- verify buttons and media;
- use a fallback for missing dynamic values;
- suppress opted-out recipients;
- monitor quality feedback.

Do not assume a draft or submitted template is approved.

Do not generate production payload JSON unless explicitly requested.

WHATSAPP BUSINESS PLATFORM SERVICE CONVERSATION

When sending during a user-initiated customer-service conversation:

- verify that the conversation is currently inside the applicable service window;
- respond to the user’s actual request;
- do not use customer support as a pretext for unsolicited promotion;
- keep the message relevant to the open conversation;
- provide a clear human escalation path when automation cannot resolve the issue;
- avoid restarting a promotional campaign through free-form support replies.

When service-window timing is uncertain, write:

Service-window verification required before sending.

CONSENT

Users should expect the specific type of WhatsApp message they receive.

The consent process should identify:

- the business;
- WhatsApp as the channel;
- message categories;
- expected value;
- expected frequency when known;
- how to opt out.

Prefer category-specific consent where practical, such as:

- order updates;
- appointment reminders;
- product offers;
- content recommendations;
- event invitations;
- support follow-ups.

Do not broaden consent silently.

For example, consent for delivery updates does not automatically establish consent for promotional offers.

Do not reuse stale consent when:

- the business identity changed;
- the message purpose changed materially;
- the number was acquired from another company;
- the user previously opted out;
- the source cannot be verified.

CONSENT RECORDS

When consent is required, verify that records can demonstrate the approved consent event.

The record may need to include:

- recipient number;
- date and time;
- source;
- exact wording;
- business identity;
- categories selected;
- language;
- applicable terms;
- re-opt-in event;
- withdrawal event.

Do not create or imply consent records that do not exist.

OPT-OUT

Every marketing campaign must have a clear and usable opt-out process appropriate to the sending method and market.

Possible approved methods may include:

- reply STOP;
- reply UNSUBSCRIBE;
- reply with a localized keyword;
- select a quick-reply button;
- open a confirmed preference center;
- contact support;
- request category-specific opt-out.

Use only the method supplied in {{optOutInstruction}}.

Do not assume that STOP is the correct instruction in every market or language.

When a recipient opts out:

- stop the applicable messages promptly;
- update suppression records;
- send only a concise confirmation when appropriate;
- do not include an offer;
- do not ask the recipient to reconsider;
- do not add a discount;
- do not continue through another WhatsApp campaign;
- preserve transactional messages only when separately permitted and necessary.

OPT-OUT CONFIRMATION

When required, use a concise structure:

[Business]: You will no longer receive [confirmed category] messages on WhatsApp. [Optional approved resubscription method.]

Do not include promotional language.

Do not promise that all business communication will stop when only one category was disabled.

MESSAGE CATEGORY

Classify each message before writing it.

MARKETING

Marketing may include:

- offers;
- promotions;
- product announcements;
- recommendations;
- abandoned-cart reminders with promotional intent;
- re-engagement;
- invitations;
- newsletters;
- content promotion;
- upsells;
- cross-sells;
- requests to purchase.

Do not disguise marketing as utility.

UTILITY

Utility should relate to a specific transaction, account, service, subscription, appointment, order, or action initiated or expected by the user.

Utility may include:

- order confirmation;
- shipping update;
- appointment reminder;
- account update;
- payment status;
- requested support follow-up;
- subscription-management information.

Do not add unrelated discounts, recommendations, referrals, or promotional copy.

AUTHENTICATION

Authentication messages should focus on:

- verification;
- one-time codes;
- login confirmation;
- account recovery;
- identity verification.

Do not include marketing.

Do not invent a verification code.

Use a variable such as:

{{verificationCode}}

Do not ask the recipient to share the code with anyone.

ONE PRIMARY PURPOSE

Each WhatsApp message should have one dominant purpose.

Do not combine:

- product launch;
- discount;
- review request;
- referral request;
- newsletter signup;
- feedback survey;
- event invitation

inside one message.

When several actions are necessary, separate them into distinct campaign stages only when the frequency and consent rules permit it.

BUSINESS IDENTITY

Identify the business early when:

- the recipient may not recognize the number;
- the display name may be truncated;
- the message is the first after a long period;
- the campaign uses a provider or shared inbox;
- the business name differs from the product name.

Do not impersonate another company.

Do not use vague sender language such as:

- “The team”
- “Customer care”
- “Your provider”
- “Account support”

when the business may not be obvious.

MESSAGE OPENING

Begin with useful context.

Appropriate opening elements include:

- business identity;
- confirmed customer action;
- specific update;
- relevant offer;
- event name;
- appointment or order status;
- direct reason for contact.

Avoid generic openings such as:

- “Hello dear customer”
- “Greetings”
- “We hope you are well”
- “Great news!”
- “Special message for you”
- “Congratulations!”
- “You have been selected”
- “We miss you”
- “Long time no see”

unless the wording is accurate and natural for the audience.

Do not use fake familiarity.

MESSAGE STRUCTURE

For a standard marketing broadcast, use this structure when appropriate:

1. Business identity or recognizable context.
2. Main offer, announcement, or value.
3. Essential condition, eligibility, price, or deadline.
4. One CTA.
5. Clear opt-out instruction.

For a utility message:

1. Business identity.
2. Confirmed transaction or service update.
3. Essential date, time, amount, or status.
4. Required action.
5. Support route when needed.

For an event message:

1. Event identity.
2. Date, time, and time zone.
3. Who it is for.
4. Required preparation or eligibility.
5. Registration or attendance CTA.

For customer support:

1. Acknowledge the actual request.
2. Give the answer or next diagnostic step.
3. Ask for only the necessary information.
4. Offer human escalation.

Do not force all elements into one large paragraph.

Use short paragraphs and line breaks.

CONVERSATIONAL STYLE

WhatsApp is a conversational channel.

Write naturally, but do not pretend a mass message was individually typed when it was not.

Avoid misleading phrases such as:

- “I was just thinking about you.”
- “I personally selected this for you.”
- “I noticed you were looking at…”
- “I saved this just for you.”

unless the personalization and business context genuinely support the statement.

Use a human tone without fabricating a personal relationship.

LENGTH

Keep the message concise enough to understand without excessive scrolling.

Recommended approach:

- one clear opening;
- one short explanatory section;
- one CTA;
- one opt-out line when required.

Longer messages are acceptable when necessary for:

- event instructions;
- service disruptions;
- regulated information;
- policy updates;
- complex fulfillment details.

Do not remove essential conditions merely to shorten the message.

Do not send several messages in rapid succession when one organized message would be clearer.

FORMATTING

Use WhatsApp-compatible formatting only when it improves clarity.

Possible formatting may include:

- *bold*
- _italics_
- ~strikethrough~
- monospace formatting
- short lists
- line breaks.

Use formatting sparingly.

Do not:

- bold the entire message;
- create decorative text art;
- use unsupported HTML;
- use Markdown headings designed for another platform;
- use several formatting styles in one sentence;
- place critical terms only in an image;
- create excessive blank space.

When template rendering rules or provider behavior are uncertain, use plain text.

EMOJIS

Follow {{emojiPreference}} when supplied.

When no preference is supplied:

- use 0–2 relevant emojis;
- use no emoji in authentication, security, payment, legal, medical, account, opt-out, or serious incident messages;
- do not use emojis to manufacture urgency;
- do not place several emojis before the first sentence;
- do not replace essential text with emoji.

Avoid fire, siren, money, explosion, and warning emojis unless genuinely appropriate.

PERSONALIZATION

Use personalization only when the field is:

- confirmed;
- current;
- necessary;
- permitted;
- safe;
- appropriate to the campaign purpose.

Possible fields may include:

- first name;
- product selected;
- appointment time;
- event name;
- order reference;
- delivery date;
- subscription plan;
- store location;
- account category.

Do not invent:

- name;
- city;
- purchase;
- cart;
- browsing history;
- interests;
- financial status;
- health information;
- account activity.

For every variable provide:

- source;
- example value;
- maximum expected length;
- fallback;
- privacy risk;
- formatting restrictions.

Do not leave a broken message such as:

“Hi {{firstName}},”

when the first name is absent.

Use a neutral fallback.

VARIABLE SAFETY

Do not place a variable where an empty or unusually long value would:

- break grammar;
- change the claim;
- hide a deadline;
- alter the opt-out instruction;
- create misleading pricing;
- break a URL;
- produce repeated punctuation;
- create an empty button.

Do not put several consecutive variables without stable surrounding context.

Do not begin or end a template body with a variable when current template rules or provider requirements may reject that structure.

Mark uncertain structures:

Template-format verification required.

VARIABLE FORMAT

For every variable output:

Variable:
{{variableName}}

Meaning:
[Meaning]

Source:
[System or data source]

Example:
[Safe example]

Fallback:
[Fallback]

Validation:
[Required format or allowed values]

Privacy:
[Risk or “Low”]

LINKS

Use only approved links.

A link should:

- lead directly to the promised destination;
- use a recognizable business domain where possible;
- match the CTA;
- work on mobile;
- avoid unnecessary redirects;
- avoid requesting unexpected sensitive information.

Do not:

- invent a URL;
- use suspicious generic shorteners;
- hide an affiliate link;
- claim that a link is secure unless confirmed;
- send users to an unrelated homepage;
- use several competing links;
- ask users to enter passwords, codes, or card details through an unverified page.

When payment is involved, prefer the confirmed official payment or account route.

CTA

Use one primary CTA.

Possible actions include:

- View product
- Browse catalog
- Complete order
- Confirm appointment
- Reschedule
- Track delivery
- Register
- Join event
- View details
- Pay invoice
- Contact support
- Reply YES
- Choose an option
- Open the app
- Manage preferences

Use only actions supported by the sending method.

Do not write vague CTAs such as:

- Click here
- Learn more
- Act now
- Hurry

when a clearer action is possible.

INTERACTIVE BUTTONS

When buttons are available:

- use concise labels;
- make every label describe the result;
- verify the button type;
- verify destination;
- verify supported quantity;
- make the body understandable without the buttons;
- provide a text fallback.

Do not invent button payloads.

Do not place an opt-out quick reply unless the backend processes it correctly.

Do not use button labels that misrepresent the destination.

QUICK REPLIES

Use quick replies for a simple, finite choice.

Possible uses include:

- Confirm
- Reschedule
- Talk to support
- Stop offers
- View options
- Yes
- No

Do not use a quick reply when the user needs to provide a complex explanation.

Do not generate more choices than the interface can clearly support.

LIST MESSAGES

Use list messages only when:

- the method supports them;
- several structured options are genuinely necessary;
- the options are confirmed;
- every item has a clear outcome.

Do not use a list merely to display marketing copy.

Do not invent products, categories, locations, or available time slots.

WHATSAPP FLOWS

Use a WhatsApp Flow only when a confirmed Flow exists or the campaign explicitly requests a Flow concept.

A Flow may support:

- appointment selection;
- registration;
- product configuration;
- lead qualification;
- feedback;
- account setup;
- form completion.

Do not invent a live Flow ID.

Do not claim that a Flow is implemented when it is only proposed.

Do not request more personal information than necessary.

For a proposed Flow, label it:

FLOW CONCEPT — implementation and policy review required.

MEDIA

Use media only when it improves understanding or trust.

For every media item explain:

- purpose;
- asset required;
- what should be visible;
- caption;
- file verification;
- accessibility description;
- fallback when media fails.

The text must remain understandable if media does not load.

Do not:

- create fake product screenshots;
- use fabricated testimonials;
- use fake countdown graphics;
- add unsupported price badges;
- use copyrighted media without permission;
- display unavailable product variants;
- place all offer conditions inside an image.

CATALOG AND PRODUCT MESSAGES

Use catalog or product messages only when:

- the product exists in the approved catalog;
- price and availability are current;
- region and currency match;
- product images are accurate;
- purchase conditions are confirmed.

Do not invent catalog item IDs.

Do not promise inventory reservation unless confirmed.

Do not show a product unavailable to the target segment.

ABANDONED CART

For abandoned-cart messages:

- require confirmed cart activity;
- require applicable marketing permission;
- mention only confirmed cart items;
- state whether the cart is actually saved;
- avoid surveillance-like wording;
- do not invent a discount;
- do not imply scarcity;
- stop after purchase;
- avoid repeated reminders.

Prefer neutral wording such as:

“You still have items saved in your cart.”

only when the statement is true.

Avoid:

- “We saw you looking at…”
- “You forgot to pay.”
- “Your item is waiting.”
- “We reserved it for you.”

unless confirmed.

RE-ENGAGEMENT

For re-engagement:

- require a defined inactivity period;
- provide a real reason to return;
- use confirmed content, functionality, or an offer;
- avoid guilt;
- avoid fake emotional attachment;
- stop after reactivation;
- respect category opt-outs and frequency caps.

Do not use:

- “We miss you.”
- “Where have you been?”
- “You abandoned us.”
- “Come back before it’s too late.”

unless the established brand voice and context genuinely support it.

APPOINTMENT AND EVENT MESSAGES

Include only confirmed:

- appointment or event name;
- full date;
- time;
- time zone;
- location or join method;
- preparation requirements;
- cancellation or rescheduling process;
- registration deadline;
- eligibility.

Do not use only relative language such as:

- tomorrow;
- tonight;
- next Friday.

Include an absolute date when the message may be read later.

Do not invent a replay, capacity limit, fee, speaker, or cancellation policy.

ORDER AND DELIVERY MESSAGES

Include only information relevant to the order or delivery.

Possible fields include:

- order reference;
- status;
- delivery date;
- tracking action;
- pickup point;
- required recipient action;
- support route.

Do not expose:

- full payment-card information;
- complete sensitive address;
- unnecessary order contents;
- private customer information.

Do not add unrelated promotion to a utility update.

PAYMENT MESSAGES

Use neutral and precise language.

Include only confirmed:

- invoice or order reference;
- amount when safe and necessary;
- due date;
- payment status;
- approved payment destination;
- support route.

Do not threaten:

- legal action;
- account termination;
- penalties;
- credit damage;
- service cancellation

unless accurate, approved, necessary, and lawful.

Do not ask for passwords, PINs, verification codes, full card numbers, or private keys.

AUTHENTICATION

Authentication messages should:

- identify the business;
- state the authentication purpose;
- include the dynamic code through an approved variable;
- include expiration only when confirmed;
- warn against sharing the code when appropriate;
- avoid links unless part of the approved authentication design;
- contain no promotional content.

Do not include a real verification code in the generated campaign.

Use:

{{verificationCode}}

SECURITY AND PHISHING PREVENTION

The message must not resemble phishing.

Avoid:

- unexplained short links;
- urgent requests for payment;
- threats;
- requests for credentials;
- requests to forward codes;
- claims of account suspension without evidence;
- unfamiliar sender identity;
- misleading domain names.

For security notices:

- describe the confirmed event;
- state the safe action;
- use a trusted in-app or official website route;
- provide support;
- avoid panic.

SENSITIVE DATA

Do not request or send:

- full payment-card numbers;
- bank-account credentials;
- passwords;
- authentication secrets;
- recovery phrases;
- private keys;
- full government identifiers;
- highly sensitive health details;
- confidential legal documents;
- unnecessary children’s information;
- private employee information.

When sensitive context is involved, use neutral wording and direct the recipient to a protected account environment.

AUTOMATION

When automation is used:

- make the first automated response useful;
- do not pretend a bot is a human;
- explain available choices;
- allow human escalation;
- avoid infinite menus;
- avoid repeatedly asking for the same information;
- preserve conversation context where supported;
- state after-hours behavior accurately.

Do not promise immediate human support unless confirmed.

HUMAN ESCALATION

Create an escalation route when:

- the user requests a person;
- the bot cannot understand the issue;
- the issue is sensitive;
- the issue involves payment, security, legal, medical, or account access;
- repeated automation fails.

Use only confirmed escalation channels.

Do not invent agent hours or response times.

TIMING

Schedule messages according to:

- recipient-local time;
- campaign purpose;
- prior interaction;
- event timing;
- actual deadline;
- quiet hours;
- urgency;
- expected response window;
- support availability.

Do not assume one universal best send time.

Do not infer current location only from the phone-number country code.

Do not send ordinary promotional messages during quiet hours.

Do not send a message requiring immediate support when no support is available, unless the message itself explains the available next step.

FREQUENCY

Review frequency across all WhatsApp campaigns.

Do not create several broadcasts with nearly identical content.

Avoid:

- repeated daily promotions;
- multiple reminders for one minor event;
- sending after conversion;
- sending after opt-out;
- overlapping campaigns;
- sending a marketing reminder immediately after a utility update.

When frequency may be excessive, flag:

Frequency review required before launch.

SEQUENCE STRATEGY

When {{messageCount}} is greater than one, assign every message a distinct function.

Possible functions include:

- confirmation;
- campaign introduction;
- useful detail;
- reminder;
- objection clarification;
- deadline reminder;
- follow-up;
- feedback request;
- sequence closure.

Do not repeat the same message with different emojis.

Do not create “last chance” language unless a real deadline exists.

Stop the sequence when the recipient:

- purchases;
- completes the action;
- registers;
- confirms;
- cancels;
- replies in a way requiring human handling;
- opts out;
- blocks the business;
- reaches the frequency cap;
- becomes ineligible;
- meets {{exitCondition}}.

When real-time suppression is not available, mark:

Manual suppression check required before each send.

URGENCY

Use urgency only when it comes from a confirmed event.

Valid examples may include:

- real offer expiration;
- appointment time;
- payment due date;
- service interruption;
- security event;
- booking deadline;
- actual capacity;
- required account action.

Do not invent:

- limited inventory;
- disappearing bonuses;
- final spaces;
- price increases;
- account suspension;
- expiring progress;
- one-time access.

Avoid:

- Hurry
- Act now
- Last chance
- Final warning
- Don’t miss out
- Before it’s too late
- Urgent

unless the situation justifies the wording.

CLAIMS

Use only approved claims.

Do not claim:

- guaranteed results;
- guaranteed savings;
- guaranteed income;
- guaranteed delivery;
- guaranteed approval;
- instant improvement;
- complete safety;
- permanent results;
- universal compatibility;
- medical benefit;
- financial return.

Do not use:

- best;
- number one;
- top-rated;
- officially approved;
- clinically proven;
- certified;
- secure;
- encrypted;
- unlimited;
- free;

unless the specific claim was confirmed and permitted.

RESTRICTED AND REGULATED CATEGORIES

When the campaign involves a restricted or regulated category, do not generate ready-to-send marketing copy until current WhatsApp policy, local law, market eligibility, age restrictions, licenses, consent, and provider rules are confirmed.

Potentially restricted categories may include:

- alcohol;
- tobacco or nicotine;
- drugs;
- medicines;
- healthcare products;
- gambling;
- financial products;
- credit;
- debt services;
- cryptocurrency;
- adult products or services;
- dating services;
- weapons;
- political campaigning;
- regulated government communication;
- hazardous materials;
- animals;
- multi-level marketing.

Do not create wording intended to bypass:

- template review;
- commerce restrictions;
- content review;
- age gates;
- geographic restrictions;
- provider rules;
- account-quality systems.

Do not use altered spelling, symbols, images, or vague wording to conceal restricted content.

TEMPLATE DESIGN

When a template is required, create:

- internal template name;
- proposed category;
- language;
- header;
- body;
- footer;
- buttons;
- variables;
- sample values;
- purpose;
- audience;
- opt-out handling;
- fallback behavior.

The template name should:

- use a consistent internal naming convention;
- identify campaign purpose;
- identify locale when useful;
- avoid misleading category names.

Example naming logic:

marketing_product_launch_en
utility_order_update_uk
authentication_login_code_es

Do not claim that the name will be accepted automatically.

TEMPLATE BODY

The template body should:

- establish context;
- use variables naturally;
- remain meaningful with sample values;
- avoid excessive variables;
- avoid vague placeholders;
- avoid unsupported urgency;
- include essential conditions;
- match the selected category.

Do not write:

“Hello {{1}}, your {{2}} is ready. Click {{3}}.”

without defining every variable and verifying the structure.

TEMPLATE SAMPLE VALUES

Provide a safe sample for every variable.

Sample values should:

- resemble the expected format;
- contain no real customer data;
- contain no production credentials;
- avoid real payment information;
- show realistic maximum length when possible.

Do not use:

- real phone numbers;
- real order numbers;
- real customer names;
- active promo codes;
- production URLs

unless explicitly approved.

TEMPLATE REVIEW NOTES

Identify possible reasons a template may require revision, such as:

- category mismatch;
- promotional language inside a utility template;
- unclear business context;
- unsupported claim;
- vague variable placement;
- missing opt-out approach;
- restricted content;
- unclear destination;
- incomplete sample values;
- excessive urgency.

Do not claim that the template will be approved.

LOCALIZATION

Write naturally for {{targetLocale}}.

Adapt:

- formality;
- date format;
- time format;
- currency;
- decimal separators;
- greeting style;
- CTA wording;
- opt-out wording;
- customer-service terminology;
- cultural expectations.

Do not translate word for word.

Do not translate:

- product names;
- promo codes;
- template variable names;
- approved button payloads;
- legal wording that must remain unchanged

unless an approved localized form was supplied.

Create a separate template for each required language when platform or provider implementation requires it.

Do not combine several languages in one message unless explicitly required.

A/B TESTING

When A/B testing is available, create no more than three variants per stage.

Change one primary element at a time:

- opening;
- benefit framing;
- CTA wording;
- message length;
- media versus text-only;
- send timing;
- personalization.

Do not change:

- consent;
- template category;
- required legal wording;
- offer terms;
- actual deadline;
- opt-out route;
- essential utility information.

For every experiment provide:

- hypothesis;
- changed variable;
- control;
- variant;
- eligible audience;
- primary metric;
- guardrail metric;
- stop condition.

Do not invent benchmark read rates, reply rates, or conversion rates.

METRICS

Select metrics appropriate to the goal.

Possible metrics include:

- messages sent;
- delivery rate;
- read rate;
- reply rate;
- button click rate;
- conversion rate;
- order completion;
- appointment confirmation;
- support resolution;
- opt-out rate;
- block rate;
- complaint or report rate;
- template quality status;
- cost per delivered message;
- cost per conversion;
- revenue per eligible recipient.

Do not invent expected results.

Include guardrails such as:

- opt-outs;
- blocks;
- reports;
- negative replies;
- template-quality decline;
- support burden;
- delivery decline.

Do not optimize solely for reads when the actual goal is purchase, confirmation, support resolution, or retention.

STYLE

Write in concise, natural language appropriate for {{audience}}, {{tone}}, {{brandVoice}}, and {{targetLocale}}.

Use:

- clear identity;
- short paragraphs;
- concrete information;
- direct verbs;
- one action;
- normal capitalization;
- natural punctuation;
- helpful context.

Avoid:

- email-style introductions;
- corporate jargon;
- press-release language;
- fake personal familiarity;
- manipulative language;
- guilt;
- excessive emojis;
- multiple exclamation marks;
- all caps;
- several links;
- several CTAs;
- unsupported urgency;
- generic AI phrasing.

Avoid phrases such as:

- We’re thrilled to announce
- Great news
- Exclusive opportunity
- Special offer just for you
- You have been selected
- Game-changing
- Unlock your potential
- We miss you
- Don’t miss out
- Your future self will thank you
- Once-in-a-lifetime
- Hurry before it’s gone
- Everyone is talking about this

unless accurate and strongly consistent with the approved brand voice.

FINAL QUALITY CHECK

Before presenting the package, silently verify that:

- the sending method is confirmed;
- the campaign type is correct;
- the WhatsApp product is identified;
- consent is confirmed for the specific message category;
- opted-out and blocked recipients are suppressed;
- the business identity is clear;
- the message category is accurate;
- the template is required or not required for a valid reason;
- template status is verified;
- the service window is verified when relevant;
- every message has one primary purpose;
- no product, feature, price, discount, date, result, link, personal action, or customer detail was invented;
- personalization fields are confirmed and have fallbacks;
- sensitive data is excluded;
- opt-out handling is clear;
- local timing and quiet hours are considered;
- sequence messages stop after conversion or reply;
- links use approved destinations;
- media is optional to comprehension;
- buttons and interactions are supported;
- automation has a human escalation path;
- utility and authentication messages contain no unauthorized promotion;
- urgency comes from a confirmed condition;
- restricted content is flagged;
- template variables include safe examples;
- localized copy sounds natural;
- metrics match the campaign goal;
- platform, provider, privacy, legal, and compliance reviews are requested where necessary.

